Results.ReviewText: I usually avoid "brands" because I am on a tight budget. The exception has always been Nescafe, which has been my firm favourite for decades. I have tried numerous other coffees but sought out special offers on Nescafe because I preferred the taste.  Sadly, I am really disappointed in the latest jar - the label has changed and I gather so have some of the production methods.  I need to use much more than before to taste it.  Is this a con to push up sales? I hope not. However, after this jar I am going to start trying the round of "own label" ones again.  Sorry, Nescafe. I may, or may not, return.
Results.Title: Not as good as before

Results.ReviewText: The flavour is lost l believe. I always valued the brown top coffee. I served it in my hairdressers. This new one is definitely missing in flavour and depth.

Results.ReviewText: I tried a jar of this a few months ago and was so disappointed. Having drunk the real Nescafe Classic (with the brown lid) for over 50 years (when they changed it from powder to granules) I cannot believe that this replacement can be the "nations  favourite".  I found it to be bitter and overly roasted as if burnt.  I even tried mixing it with a full jar of the supermarkets own brand "Gold"  which was very bland but served to cut the new Nescafe bitterness to a more palatable taste. Once I had finished that jar I found I was still able to buy the brown lid Nescafe Classic from other bargain supermarkets so have been stocking up with the 200g jars from them. I still enjoy my daily intake of Nescafe but Classic, not Original.
Results.Title: Poor expensive replacement for Nescafe Classic

ClientResponses.Response:
Hi, we're really sorry to hear about your disappointment with the recent changes we've made to our Nescafé Original.

We worked on trying to make it a more enjoyable cup for you by developing some tech that in two steps helps to maintain the full flavour and aroma of our Nescafé Original, whilst taking out harsher and bitter compounds (Double Filter).

We've made a note of your comments & will be passing them on to the rest of the team.

Results.ReviewText:
I often drink "real bean" coffee, but often the most practical means of having a nice cup is via instant granules. Having tried many other brands at home, in the office, or in hotels, etc. I still feel that Nescafe is the best instant coffee available. Unlike many others, the granules all go to making the best cup available, rather than some competitors' brands which stick to the teaspoon and don't dissolve properly.
A small tip, though; I find that adding milk to the drink AFTER the hot water gives better flavour than adding it to the granules - I think the boiling water does something to the milk if you do it in the "wrong" order, but maybe that's just me.
Results.Title: Great instant coffee.

Results.ReviewText:
We love the taste of double filtered Nescafe Original which is easily recognisable with its iconic red lid. My Mum first introduced me to it and we have been buying it ever since. 
You could taste the quality in this coffee, compared to that of other brands.
You can even buy refill packs to fill up your jar when it is empty. This is so useful, eco-friendly and economical. 
I always read the guidelines on the jar and check the best before dates. 
One tip I have is never put a wet spoon into the coffee jar when spooning in the coffee granules into your cup. The coffee in the jar can become damp and will spoil.
The cost of the coffee is good value for money and worth trying. You will not be disappointed :D
